{{ill|Yutokunin|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yutokunin|qq=}} (also rendered as {{ill|Utokunin|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utokunin|qq=}}) '''Yutokunin''' (有徳人, also rendered as 有得人) refers to the wealthy class in medieval Japan. Although these people originally belonged to low social status (such as farmers or local gōn [land stewards]), they attained wealth and became prominent merchants or estate officials. The term “Yutoku” originally comes from a Buddhist term meaning “possessing virtue” (徳) and later came to be associated with profit (得) because wealthy people—fearing divine retribution for greed or seeking to acquire merit—actively made donations to temples and shrines. In medieval and early modern Japanese literature such as kana-zōshi and ukiyo-zōshi, such individuals are often described as “Yutokunin” or “Chōja” (rich men).
The emergence of this class is closely connected with the development of a monetary economy from the later Kamakura period onward, when prosperous merchant groups (including tsuchikura, sake-ya, and tomaru) and their charitable activities began to attract public attention. == References == * [[Kuroda Toshio]] “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi Daijiten|qq=}} Vol. 2 (吉川弘文館, 1980) ISBN 978-4-642-00502-9. * [[Wakida Haruko]] “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Nihon Shidaijiten|ja|日本史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shidaijiten|qq=}} Vol. 1 (平凡社, 1992) ISBN 978-4-582-13101-7. * Watanabe Kōshi, “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|qq=}} Vol. 1 (小学館, 2001) ISBN 978-4-095-23001-6. * Komori Masaaki, “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Nihon Chūsei Shiji-ten|ja|日本中世史事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Chūsei Shiji-ten|qq=}} (朝倉書店, 2008) ISBN 978-4-254-53015-5. == See Also == * {{ill|Chōja|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōja|qq=}} (Rich men) * {{ill|Yutoku Coins|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yutoku Coins|qq=}} (Yutokunin Coins)
