The emergence of this class is closely connected with the development of a monetary economy from the later Kamakura period onward, when prosperous merchant groups (including tsuchikura, sake-ya, and tomaru) and their charitable activities began to attract public attention. == References == * [[:en:Kuroda Toshio|Kuroda Toshio]] “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi Daijiten|qq=|1=Kokushi Daijiten|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q6426904}} Vol. 2 (吉川弘文館, 1980) ISBN 978-4-642-00502-9. * [[Wakida Haruko]] “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Nihon Shidaijiten|ja|日本史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shidaijiten|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} Vol. 1 (平凡社, 1992) ISBN 978-4-582-13101-7. * Watanabe Kōshi, “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|qid=Q135524488}} Vol. 1 (小学館, 2001) ISBN 978-4-095-23001-6. * Komori Masaaki, “Yutokunin,” in {{ill|Nihon Chūsei Shiji-ten|ja|日本中世史事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Chūsei Shiji-ten|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (朝倉書店, 2008) ISBN 978-4-254-53015-5. == See Also == * {{ill|Chōja|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōja|qq=}} (Rich men) * {{ill|Yutoku Coins|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yutoku Coins|qq=}} (Yutokunin Coins)
